"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521979","Department of Health","false","2016-06-10","<p>The Department has transferred records to The National Archives that relate to contaminated blood. There are parts of the documents which are not publicly available as they relate to personal information about named individuals. The names and other identifying information are closed to the public until the individual has reached 100 years of age.</p><p> </p><p>The publication of the names of patients, or other identifying information such as their address and medical condition, would breach their privacy under the Data Protection Act. When the individual reaches 100 years of age, the unredacted documents will be made available. This is consistent with other records held by The National Archives which contains personal and sensitive information.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-06-10T11:09:31.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521979/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521979/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521979/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Blood: Contamination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will remove the restriction that prohibits the publication of official government documents relating to the contaminated blood scandal under the 100-year rule.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","38754"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521980","Department of Health","false","2016-06-10","<p>Records relating to contaminated blood up to the year 1995 have been transferred to The National Archives for permanent preservation, and are available electronically on their website at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C14522322" target="_blank">http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C14522322</a></p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-06-10T11:00:02.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521980/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521980/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521980/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Blood: Contamination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, on what date he plans to publish official government documents relating to contaminated blood that are held under the 100-year rule.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","38755"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521981","Department of Health","false","2016-06-10","<p>We do not recognise that a 100 year rule has been established for the retention of records. The Department works to the guidance published by The National Archives on the appraisal and selection of records which are retained and transferred for permanent preservation.</p><p> </p><p>The records relating to contaminated blood have been published in response to obligations under the Freedom of Information Act, and records relating to the period between 1986 and 1995 transferred to The National Archives.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-06-10T11:04:06.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521981/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521981/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521981/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Blood: Contamination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many official government documents are held under the 100-year rule relating to the contaminated blood scandal.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","38757"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521982","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>The Tackling Corruption Together conference on 11 May was organised by a consortium of civil society organisations, businesses and the Commonwealth Secretariat. The government was not responsible for the guest list.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-06-06T10:13:31.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521982/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521982/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521982/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-05-26","Tackling Corruption Together Conference","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, which members of the Inter-Ministerial Group on Corruption attended the Tackling Corruption Together conference held on 11 May 2016.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","38873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521983","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>The full list of attendees is now available on Gov.UK at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/anti-corruption-summit-attendance-list" target="_blank"><strong>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/anti-corruption-summit-attendance-list</strong></a></p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-06-06T10:10:26.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521983/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521983/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521983/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-05-26","Anti-corruption Summit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, which members of the Inter-Ministerial Group on Corruption attended the Anti-Corruption Summit on 12 May 2016.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","38874"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521984","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>The guidelines on measuring and managing supplier performance are provided in the Contract Management Standards, available on the Crown Commercial Service website. <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/commercial-capability-contract-management-standards" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/commercial-capability-contract-management-standards</a></p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-06-06T10:17:01.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521984/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521984/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521984/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-05-26","Public Sector: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what guidelines there are for measuring the performance of contractors delivering public services.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","38760"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521985","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-06-06T15:26:05.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521985/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521985/answer","UKSA response to  38748.pdf","UKSA response to  38748.pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - Veterans on Census","UKSA Letter to Member - Veterans on Census","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521985/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-05-26","Armed Forces: Census","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will make it his policy that questions to determine the number of veterans, armed forces personnel and reservists be included in the next census.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","38748"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521986","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>The Public Contracts Regulations 2015 include various grounds under which individual suppliers must or may be excluded from a specific procurement process. Mandatory grounds for exclusion include convictions for bribery, money laundering and fraud. Discretionary grounds include bankruptcy and grave professional misconduct. Decisions to exclude suppliers must be taken by individual contracting authorities on a case-by-case basis.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-06-06T16:33:35.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521986/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521986/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521986/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-05-26","Public Sector: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what criteria are used to decide whether people are fit and proper persons to engage with Government as directors of companies or not-for-profit ventures.","false","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","38698"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521987","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-09","<p>A figure for spend on non-payroll staff in the Government Digital Service in 2015-16 will be available after Cabinet Office Accounts are audited and published, which is planned in the summer.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-06-09T10:55:39.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521987/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521987/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521987/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521987/answer/previousversion/2150","Biography information for Matt Hancock","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-05-26","Government Digital Service: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate he has made of the amount spent on non-payroll staff in the Government Digital Service in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","38804"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521988","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>The employment of staff is delegated to individual departments. Decisions on whether to engage non-payroll staff are taken by individual departments taking into account their business needs and the circumstances of the vacancy. The information requested on these staff is not held centrally by the Cabinet Office.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","38790 ; 38806","2016-06-06T10:15:05.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521988/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521988/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521988/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-05-26","Government Departments: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many non-payroll staff were hired by each government department in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","38805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521989","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>The employment of staff is delegated to individual departments. Decisions on whether to engage non-payroll staff are taken by individual departments taking into account their business needs and the circumstances of the vacancy. The information requested on these staff is not held centrally by the Cabinet Office.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","38790 ; 38805","2016-06-06T10:15:05.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521989/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521989/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521989/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-05-26","Government Departments: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much was spent from the public purse on non-payroll staff in all government departments in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","38806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521990","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-08","<p>Copies of the Government's published documents on the Referendum are available in the Libraries of both Houses. It is not normal practice to publish letters to members of the public and stakeholders. Costs relating to the Referendum will be accounted for in the usual way in Annual Report and Accounts.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose","38825","2016-06-08T16:06:27.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521990/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521990/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521990/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-05-26","Cabinet Office: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will place in the Library copies of all letters, leaflets and other material from his Department circulated to (a) stakeholders and (b) members of the public on the EU Referendum; what the costs of the production and distribution of that material has been since 1 January 2016; and what he estimates the cost of any further production and distribution of such material will be between 6 May 2016 and 23 June 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","William Wragg","38811"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521991","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-06","<p>The UK multi-agency taskforce has begun analytical work on all the data published by the International Consortium of Investigative Journalists (ICIJ), in addition to a wide range of other intelligence which includes more than 700 HM Revenue and Customs leads with a connection to Panama. As part of this work, the task force is currently analysing and reviewing the names and addresses published by the ICIJ with alleged links to the UK and Mossack Fonseca.</p><p> </p><p>While the sensitivity of the work means that it will not be possible to give a running commentary on any investigations, or number of investigations, Parliament will be kept updated on any significant developments.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-06-06T16:32:50.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521991/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521991/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521991/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-26","Tax Evasion","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to his Department's news story of 10 April 2016, UK launches cross-government taskforce on the Panama Papers, (a) how many leads the multi-agency taskforce is currently investigating and (b) how many of those leads have a direct link to the leaked documents relating to the operations of Mossack Fonseca.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","38724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521992","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-10","<p>Figure 16 of the National Audit Office’s (NAO) Tackling Tax Fraud report, relates to the (tax) revenue loss prevented (RLP) as a result of HM Revenue and Customs’ (HMRC) criminal investigations. RLP represents the revenue that would have been lost in year if HMRC had not taken action – for example, stopping someone claiming VAT repayments that were not due to them.</p><p> </p><p>In addition to RLP, and not included in figure 16 of the NAO report, HMRC also recovers money through confiscation and cash forfeiture. Following a successful prosecution, HMRC and the prosecuting authority will consider whether to pursue confiscation under the Proceeds of Crime Act 2002. In 2014/15 – the period of the NAO report - HMRC recovered over £24 million in this way.</p><p> </p><p>In the same period, HMRC also secured the following confiscation orders:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Value of Orders made</p></td><td><p>Number of Orders</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£0 to £4,999*</p></td><td><p>38</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£5,000 to £9,999</p></td><td><p>13</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£10,000 to £49,999</p></td><td><p>40</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£50,000 to £99,999</p></td><td><p>22</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£100,000 to £499,999</p></td><td><p>28</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£500,000 to £999,999</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£1 million and over</p></td><td><p>9</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>*<sub>These figure includes what are known as 'nominal orders' where it is impossible to identify recoverable property but allows HMRC and the prosecuting authorities’ scope to re-investigate if property is subsequently identified. An increase in order is then applicable to more accurately reflect the benefit figure assessed.</sub></p><p> </p><p>HMRC also works with other law enforcement agencies to collect tax evaded in the course of other criminal conduct – for example, drugs offences. In 2014/15 this brought in over £8 million to the Exchequer.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-06-10T08:08:54.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521992/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521992/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521992/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-26","Taxation: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the report, Tackling Tax Fraud, published by the National Audit Office in December 2015, how much of the tax revenue at stake for successful prosecutions in each range in Table 16 was recovered.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","38713"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521993","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-10","<p>I refer the Hon Member to the Prime Minister's response of 25th May 2016. This information is not collated centrally by the Department.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-06-10T08:25:19.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521993/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521993/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521993/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-26","Treasury: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 25 May 2016 to Question 37198, how many of the leaflets entitled Why the Government believes that voting to remain in the European Union is the best decision for the UK have been returned to his Department; and what the postage cost to the Government has been of such returns.","true","Biography information for Tom Pursglove","Corby","Tom Pursglove","38780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521994","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-09","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given by the Minister for the Cabinet Office on 8 June 2016 to Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-05-26/38811/" target="_blank">38811</a>.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-06-09T14:48:06.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521994/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521994/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521994/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-26","Treasury: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will place in the Library copies of all letters, leaflets and other material from his Department circulated to (a) stakeholders and (b) members of the public on the EU Referendum; what the costs of the production and distribution of that material has been since 1 January 2016; and what he estimates the cost of any further production and distribution of such material will be between 6 May 2016 and 23 June 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","William Wragg","38828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521995","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-06","<p>There are upward of 100 people currently involved in the multi-agency Taskforce, some spending more of their time working on taskforce activity than others.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-06-06T16:32:24.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521995/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521995/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521995/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-26","Tax Evasion","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether any of the staff of the cross-agency taskforce examining the Panama Papers are working only on that taskforce.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","38872"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521996","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-06","<p>Foreign purchasers of UK property are liable to Stamp Duty Land Tax (SDLT). Since 1 April 2016 higher rates of SDLT have been charged on purchases of additional residential properties, such as second homes and buy-to-let properties.</p><p> </p><p>For the purposes of the higher rates, properties owned globally are taken into consideration when deciding whether the charges should apply to a given purchase. In addition to this, non-residents contribute to the tax system through SDLT, council tax and potentially capital gains tax.</p><p> </p><p>The Government believes it has the right approach to ensuring all purchasers, including foreign investors, pay their fair share of tax. However, all taxes are kept under review.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-06-06T14:35:14.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521996/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521996/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521996/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-26","Stamp Duty Land Tax: Foreign Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of introducing an additional rate of stamp duty on property purchases by foreign investors.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","38852"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521997","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-06","<p>Finance Bill 2016 contains provisions to exclude all remaining energy generation from the tax advantaged venture capital schemes, and makes technical clarifications to ensure the rules work as intended. These measures were announced at Autumn Statement 2015 and Budget 2016 respectively. These changes apply for investments made on or after 6 April 2016.</p><p> </p><p>The government published tax information and impact notes for these measures, which can be found at https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/income-tax-exclusion-of-energy-generation-from-venture-capital-schemes and https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/income-tax-enterprise-investment-scheme-and-venture-capital-trusts.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-06-06T16:33:16.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521997/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521997/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521997/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-26","Capital Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the effect on business and investor confidence of potential retroactive changes being made to (a) Enterprise Investment Schemes, (b) Venture Capital Trusts and (c) other investment incentives.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Reynolds","Stalybridge and Hyde","Jonathan Reynolds","38857"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521998","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-10","<p>The Government has made it clear that UK rates of Child benefit should not be paid to EU children overseas. The Government paper, “The best of both worlds: the United Kingdom’s special status in a reformed European Union” https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-best-of-both-worlds-the-united-kingdoms-special-status-in-a-reformed-european-union, sets out what was agreed at the February European council.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-06-10T08:35:58.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521998/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521998/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521998/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-26","Child Benefit: EEA Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to HM Revenue and Custom's publication Statistics on recently arrived non-UK EEA nationals subject to income tax and National Insurance contributions or receiving HMRC administered benefits of May 2016, how many child benefit claims of what amount were made by (a) non-UK EEA nationals and (b) recently arrived non-UK EEA nationals in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris","38889"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521999","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-10","<p>At March European Council, the Prime Minister secured the agreement of all Member States to European Council Conclusions which welcomed ‘the intention of the Commission to include proposals for increased flexibility for Member States with respect to reduced rates of VAT, which would provide the option to Member States of VAT zero rating of sanitary products‎'.</p><p> </p><p>Following that meeting, the issue of a zero-rate of VAT on sanitary products was discussed on 17, 19 and 29 April and 10 May. Most recently, on 25 May, ECOFIN agreed Conclusions which called for a proposal ‘foreseeing an option to Member States of VAT reduced or zero rating for women’s sanitary products at the earliest opportunity’.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-06-10T08:05:05.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521999/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521999/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521999/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-26","Sanitary Protection: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, on what dates in each of the last three months officials of his Department have discussed the UK's plans for an exemption of VAT on sanitary products with the European Commission.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","38611"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522000","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-10","<p>On 3 November 2015, I wrote to Commissioner Pierre Moscovici and other Member States setting out the Government view that EU Member States should have full discretion over what rate of VAT they apply to sanitary products. I reiterated that call in a letter to Commissioner Pierre Moscovici on 17 December 2015.</p><p> </p><p>At the March European Council, the Prime Minister secured the agreement of all Member States to European Council Conclusions which welcomed ‘the intention of the Commission to include proposals for increased flexibility for Member States with respect to reduced rates of VAT, which would provide the option to Member States of VAT zero rating of sanitary products‎'.</p><p> </p><p>The Chancellor wrote to Pierre Moscovici on 19 April, requesting that the Commission urgently bring forward a specific proposal to cover VAT rates on sanitary products.</p><p> </p><p>On 25 May ECOFIN agreed Conclusions which called for a proposal ‘foreseeing an option to Member States of VAT reduced or zero rating for women’s sanitary products at the earliest opportunity’.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-06-10T07:57:48.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522000/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522000/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522000/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-26","Sanitary Protection: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will publish all correspondence between his Department and the European Commission on the UK's request to introduce a zero rate of VAT on women's sanitary products.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","38612"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522001","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-10","<p>The zero rate of VAT for sanitary products will take effect as soon as possible after Royal Assent of the Finance Bill, with some notice to retailers.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-06-10T08:20:51.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522001/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522001/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522001/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-26","Sanitary Protection: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, on what date he expects  the planned removal of VAT on women's sanitary products to take effect.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","38610"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522002","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-06","<p>The cross-agency task force will be led by HM Revenue and Customs and the National Crime Agency in collaboration with all relevant agencies, including the Serious Fraud Office and the Financial Conduct Authority. Between them, these agencies have some of the most sophisticated technology, experts and resources to tackle money laundering and tax evasion anywhere in the world.</p><p>The funding for the taskforce will be distributed as appropriate via the supplementary estimates process.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-06-06T16:31:56.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522002/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522002/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522002/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-26","Tax Evasion","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Answer of 12 May 2016 to Question 36479, to where the £10 million funding for the multi-agency taskforce has been allocated; and what proportion of that funding has not yet been allocated.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","38701"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522003","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-10","<p>As set out on pages 145 to 150 of HM Treasury’s analysis on the long-term economic impact of EU membership and the alternatives: “Successful EU-wide economic reform would make a substantial positive contribution to UK economic prospects. Combining the 4 key areas of EU economic reform gives an estimate of the benefits of reform of up to 4% of UK GDP after 15 years. In 2015 terms, this would mean up to an extra £2,800 a year of GDP per household.”</p><p> </p><p>This estimate of the impact of additional reform for the UK inside the EU is constructed and quantified around the best available evidence on 4 reform priorities: Single Market for services, Digital Single Market, single energy market and external trade agreements (i.e. those with non-EU countries).</p><p> </p><p>Further to the quantified benefits of EU reforms that are agreed or in the process of being implemented, there are other additional EU reforms that will bring benefits but are unquantified and not included in the “4% of UK GDP after 15 years” estimate. The UK could benefit from reduced EU regulatory burdens: the UK’s new settlement includes a commitment to reduce the regulatory burden on businesses, particularly small and medium-sized businesses, with specific targets established in key sectors. The EU has also committed to deliver a Capital Markets Union to deepen and integrate the EU’s capital markets.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-06-10T08:37:09.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522003/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522003/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522003/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-26","Economic Growth: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to page 148 of his Department's analysis: the long-term economic impact of EU membership and the alternatives, Cm 9250, if he will set out which EU regulations are to be reformed to cause an increase in UK gross domestic product of four per cent after 15 years.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","William Wragg","38690"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522004","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-06","<p>The government will shortly be consulting on the detail of the soft drinks industry levy, and we will publish an initial impact assessment alongside the consultation. This assessment will be updated and refined when the policy detail is finalised.</p><p> </p><p>For Finance Bill measures, HMRC provide a Tax Impact Information Note alongside the draft Finance Bill legislation, which we expect to publish in the winter.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-06-06T14:22:46.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522004/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522004/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522004/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-26","Soft Drinks: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the soft drinks industry levy on levels of employment; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","North East Somerset","Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","38692"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522005","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-06","<p>Since 2010 the Chancellor has adopted the independent economic and public finance forecasts produced by the Office for Budget Responsibility (OBR) as the UK’s official forecasts. The OBR is required to take into account the effect of government policies in its analysis. The OBR sets out its forecasts in its Economic and Fiscal Outlook (EFO), which includes a full breakdown of how the forecast is composed and any explanations.</p><p> </p><p>The OBR’s Economic and Fiscal Outlook document, published at Budget 2016, summarised the OBR’s views. The document noted that the OBR expect the levy to be passed onto the price paid by consumers. On this basis the OBR expected it to add around a quarter of a percentage point to CPI and RPI inflation in 2018-19.</p><p> </p><p>The government maintains that it is up to soft drinks companies how they respond to the levy. If companies reformulate their drinks to contain less sugar – as many are already doing – then they will not have to pay the levy. Companies two years to continue working on this before the levy begins. They do not need to pass the levy onto consumers.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-06-06T14:21:07.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522005/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522005/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522005/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-26","Soft Drinks: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he has made an estimate of the potential effect of the soft drinks industry levy on the (a) consumer price index and (b) cost of uprating index-linked benefits; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","North East Somerset","Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","38693"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522006","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-06","<p>HM Revenue and Customs’ (HMRC) customer service performance was comprehensively reviewed by the independent National Audit Office in a report published on May 25<sup>th</sup> 2016.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC have publically acknowledged and apologised for the deterioration in performance early in 2015. Since then HMRC have recovered and are now providing their best service levels in years.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-06-06T16:31:03.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522006/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522006/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522006/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-26","Revenue and Customs","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Answer of 12 February 2016 to Question 26015, when he plans to undertake a comprehensive review of the performance of HM Revenue and Customs in dealing with correspondence and telephone calls from members of the public.","false","Biography information for Tommy Sheppard","Edinburgh East","Tommy Sheppard","38687"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522007","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-06","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) does not break down its management statistics by area or region of the UK and does not have the ability to do so. All statistics are prepared on a National level.</p><p> </p><p>Over the past six months, HMRC has answered calls across all of its helplines in an average of 6 minutes. Its performance data will be published in its Annual Report and following the year end audit.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-06-06T16:31:25.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522007/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522007/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522007/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-26","Revenue and Customs: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Answer of 2 February 2016 to Question 24013, if he will publish HM Revenue and Customs call handling data for (a) London and (b) each region of the UK.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","38688"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522008","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-06-10","<p>The Government is consulting until 10 July on legislation and guidance for a corporate offence of failure to prevent the criminal facilitation of tax evasion.</p><p> </p><p>Separately, The Prime Minister announced on 11 May that the Government will consult on extending the criminal offence of “failure to prevent” to other economic crimes such as fraud and money laundering.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-06-10T09:40:38.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522008/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522008/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522008/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-05-26","Companies: Criminal Liability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what plans he has to bring forward legislative proposals to make banks and large companies criminally responsible for employees who embezzle funds, launder money and evade tax.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","38677"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522009","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-06","<p>The UK has applied a VAT reduced rate of 5% on 11 different types of energy saving materials since 2001 and that existing reduced rate remains in place and is unchanged.</p><p> </p><p>Following the judgement by the Court of Justice of the European Union, we published a consultation late last year on this complex issue. We are considering the responses to this consultation.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-06-06T16:34:46.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522009/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522009/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522009/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-26","Housing Improvement: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when the Government plans to bring forward legislative proposals to comply with the policy of the European Court of Justice of 4 June 2015 on the rate of VAT on energy saving materials, Case C-161/14 Commission v United Kingdom.","false","Biography information for John Redwood","Wokingham","John Redwood","38626"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522010","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-10","<p>To date there has been no formal proposal for a European Tax Identification Number (EU TIN), and this European Parliament committee has no power to put forward a proposal in the tax space.</p><p> </p><p>Tax is a Member State competence. All Member States have to agree with unanimity on tax proposals, so if a proposal were brought forward regarding an EU TIN the UK would need to formally agree in order for it to proceed.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-06-10T07:58:58.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522010/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522010/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522010/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-26","Taxation: EU Action","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential implications of the EU Economic and Monetary Affairs Committee's decision of 27 May 2016 to introduce European Taxpayer Identification Numbers for the administration of tax in the UK.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","38668"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522011","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-13","<p>In the Government’s International Education Strategy, published in July 2013, the value of international higher education students to the UK was valued at £9.7bn. Information for Sunderland-specifically is not available.</p><p>The international education strategy can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/international-education-strategy-global-growth-and-prosperity" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/international-education-strategy-global-growth-and-prosperity</a></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-06-13T10:33:29.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522011/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522011/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522011/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-05-26","Sunderland University: Overseas Students","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate he has made of the benefits of international students at the University of Sunderland to the economy of Sunderland in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","38878"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522012","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-10","<p>The taskforce will report jointly to the Chancellor and to the Home Secretary. It will provide a progress report later this year which will set out the taskforce’s initial assessment of the information in the Panama papers and proposed actions for further analysis and strategy for pursuing any evidence found of wrongdoing and regulatory breaches.</p><p> </p><p>The taskforce is jointly led by HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) and the National Crime Agency (NCA), with other partners including the Serious Fraud Office (SFO) and Financial Conduct Authority. The NCA, HMRC and others already regularly work together to tackle serious and organised financial crime of many types.</p><p> </p><p>The UK multi-agency taskforce has begun analytical work on all the data published by the International Consortium of Investigative Journalists (ICIJ), in addition to continuing to develop a wide range of other intelligence which includes more than 700 HMRC leads with a connection to Panama. As part of this work, the task force is currently analysing and reviewing the names and addresses published by the ICIJ with alleged links to the UK and Mossack Fonseca.</p><p> </p><p>While the sensitivity of the work means that it will not be possible to give a running commentary on any investigations, or number of investigations, Parliament will be kept updated on any significant developments.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","38862 ; 38869","2016-06-10T08:03:49.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522012/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522012/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522012/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-26","Tax Evasion","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, who in Government is responsible for overseeing the cross-agency taskforce set up to examine the Panama Papers.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","38863"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522013","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-10","<p>The taskforce will report jointly to the Chancellor and to the Home Secretary. It will provide a progress report later this year which will set out the taskforce’s initial assessment of the information in the Panama papers and proposed actions for further analysis and strategy for pursuing any evidence found of wrongdoing and regulatory breaches.</p><p> </p><p>The taskforce is jointly led by HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) and the National Crime Agency (NCA), with other partners including the Serious Fraud Office (SFO) and Financial Conduct Authority. The NCA, HMRC and others already regularly work together to tackle serious and organised financial crime of many types.</p><p> </p><p>The UK multi-agency taskforce has begun analytical work on all the data published by the International Consortium of Investigative Journalists (ICIJ), in addition to continuing to develop a wide range of other intelligence which includes more than 700 HMRC leads with a connection to Panama. As part of this work, the task force is currently analysing and reviewing the names and addresses published by the ICIJ with alleged links to the UK and Mossack Fonseca.</p><p> </p><p>While the sensitivity of the work means that it will not be possible to give a running commentary on any investigations, or number of investigations, Parliament will be kept updated on any significant developments.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","38863 ; 38869","2016-06-10T08:03:49.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522013/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522013/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522013/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-26","Tax Evasion","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, which government department has responsibility for the cross-agency taskforce established to examine the Panama Papers.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","38862"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522014","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-10","<p>The Government has negotiated a new settlement that will enable the UK to have a new emergency brake to limit full access to in-work benefits by newly arrived EU workers for up to 4 years when they enter our labour market. This will be in force for 7 years. The Government paper “The best of both worlds: the United Kingdom’s special status in a reformed European Union” https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-best-of-both-worlds-the-united-kingdoms-special-status-in-a-reformed-european-union, sets out what was agreed at the February European council.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-06-10T08:33:21.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522014/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522014/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522014/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-26","Welfare Tax Credits: EEA Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the HM Revenue and Customs publication, entitled Tax Credits Statistics on non-UK EEA Nationals, of 22 February 2016, how many (a) in-work and (b) out-of-work claims of what amount were made by families with at least one (i) EEA national and (ii) recently arrived EEA national in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris","38886"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522015","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-10","<p>The taskforce will report jointly to the Chancellor and to the Home Secretary. It will provide a progress report later this year which will set out the taskforce’s initial assessment of the information in the Panama papers and proposed actions for further analysis and strategy for pursuing any evidence found of wrongdoing and regulatory breaches.</p><p> </p><p>The taskforce is jointly led by HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) and the National Crime Agency (NCA), with other partners including the Serious Fraud Office (SFO) and Financial Conduct Authority. The NCA, HMRC and others already regularly work together to tackle serious and organised financial crime of many types.</p><p> </p><p>The UK multi-agency taskforce has begun analytical work on all the data published by the International Consortium of Investigative Journalists (ICIJ), in addition to continuing to develop a wide range of other intelligence which includes more than 700 HMRC leads with a connection to Panama. As part of this work, the task force is currently analysing and reviewing the names and addresses published by the ICIJ with alleged links to the UK and Mossack Fonseca.</p><p> </p><p>While the sensitivity of the work means that it will not be possible to give a running commentary on any investigations, or number of investigations, Parliament will be kept updated on any significant developments.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","38862 ; 38863","2016-06-10T08:03:49.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522015/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522015/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522015/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-26","Tax Evasion","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what activity the cross-agency taskforce on the Panama Papers has undertaken since it was established.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","38869"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522016","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-10","<p>HM Treasury’s approach to estimating the net cost of the EU budget to the UK over the long term is set out in Annex B of HM Treasury Analysis: the long-term economic impact of EU membership and the alternatives, publicly available at the following link:</p><p> </p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/517415/treasury_analysis_economic_impact_of_eu_membership_web.pd</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-06-10T08:39:05.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522016/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522016/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522016/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-26","EU Budget: Contributions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the level and amount of the UK EU rebate in each year to 2030.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","William Wragg","38927"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522017","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-10","<p>Staff within the longstanding International and EU group lead on providing advice to Ministers on EU and EU related issues. Staff within other groups may also provide advice or analysis on EU issues as required.</p><p> </p><p>HM Treasury do not routinely capture information about each employee’s specific work. To provide information capturing the length of time official’s worked specifically on the referendum would incur disproportionate costs. Information on HM Treasury staff salaries is published on this link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-staff-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-staff-data</a></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-06-10T08:11:02.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522017/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522017/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522017/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-26","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many (a) press officers and (b) other officials of his Department have been or are undertaking work related to the referendum on UK membership of the EU; for how long each such official has been working on that matter; and what the salary is of each such official.","false","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris","38924"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522018","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-08","<p>The Government published on 6<sup>th</sup> April 2016 the total cost of producing, distributing and publicising the Government’s leaflet on the EU Referendum, including digital promotion and the production of eureferndum.gov.uk. Wider costs relating to the Referendum will be accounted for in the usual way in Annual Report and Accounts.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2016-06-08T16:10:27.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522018/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522018/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522018/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-05-26","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much the Government (a) has spent to date and (b) plans to spend before 23 June 2016 on promoting the Government's policy on the UK's membership of the EU.","false","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris","38929"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522019","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-08","<p>HM Treasury does not publish estimates of the impact of the economic performance of the euro area or other EU Member States on the UK economy or public finances. The Treasury continuously monitors global economic developments as part of the normal process of domestic policy development.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-06-08T10:50:57.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522019/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522019/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522019/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-26","Economic Situation: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on (a) the UK economy and (b) the public finances of a slowdown in the economies (i) in the Eurozone and (ii) of other EU member states.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","William Wragg","38946"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522020","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-08","<p>HM Treasury does not publish estimates of the effect of economic events in other EU Member States on the UK economy. The Treasury continuously monitors global economic developments as part of the normal process of domestic policy development.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-06-08T10:49:02.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522020/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522020/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522020/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-26","Economic Situation: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the economic events in other EU member states that would have an adverse impact on the UK economy; and what steps he has taken to model the effects of such risks.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","William Wragg","38947"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522021","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-08","<p>HM Treasury does not publish estimates of the effect of higher unemployment levels in the euro area or other EU Member States on the UK economy or public finances. The Treasury continuously monitors global economic developments as part of the normal process of domestic policy development.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-06-08T10:53:11.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522021/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522021/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522021/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-26","Unemployment: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on (a) the UK economy and (b) public finances of higher unemployment levels in (i) the Eurozone and (ii) other EU member states.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","William Wragg","38948"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522022","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-10","<p>Help to Buy covers a range of different schemes, offering home ownership options for a wide range of people. We are continuing to expand and improve access to Help to Buy, as shown by the development of London Help to Buy which offers equity loans of up to 40%, in recognition of affordability issues resulting from higher house prices in the capital.</p><p>On top of this, Help to Buy: Equity Loan enables people to buy a new-build home, with a deposit of as little as 5%; Help to Buy: ISA gives first-time buyers a 25% bonus on savings; and Help to Buy: Shared Ownership enables people to buy 25% to 75% of their home's value and pay rent on the rest.</p><p>The Department promotes Help to Buy through dedicated websites and other media, to ensure people are aware of all these options.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-06-10T13:27:31.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522022/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522022/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522022/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-26","Help to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what plans his Department has to improve access to the Help to Buy scheme.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","38926"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522023","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-06","<p>Local planning authorities are best placed to decide whether changes to estimated population and housing need levels in their area would meet the very special circumstances for permitting inappropriate development in the Green Belt, and the exceptional circumstances in which Green Belt boundaries may be adjusted through the Local Plan process.</p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-06-06T15:30:00.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522023/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522023/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522023/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-26","Green Belt","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will take steps to review his policy on the green belt to take account of changes in the levels of migration.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","38657"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522024","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-10","<p>In February 2012, we published <em>Creating the Conditions for integration</em> which is built around the five key contributors to an integrated society<em>:</em></p><ul><li>common ground - a clear sense of shared aspirations and values, which celebrates what we have in common rather than our differences</li><li>responsibility - a strong sense of our mutual commitments and obligations, which brings personal and social responsibility</li><li>social mobility - people able to realise their potential to get on in life</li><li>participation and empowerment - people of all backgrounds have opportunities to take part, be heard and take decisions in local and national life</li><li>tackling intolerance and extremism - a robust response to threats, whether discrimination, extremism or disorder, that deepen division and increase tensions.</li></ul><p>The Community Life Survey 2014-15 shows a well-integrated society with 87% of people reporting they belong strongly to Britain and 86% that their local area is a place where people from different backgrounds get on well together. But we know that some communities and places still face challenges, tensions and missed opportunities. That is why the Prime Minister asked Louise Casey to carry out a review into boosting opportunity and integration in the most isolated and deprived communities. The results of the review will inform a major new Cohesive Communities Programme.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-06-10T13:26:34.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522024/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522024/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522024/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-26","Community Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what indicators the Government uses to determine levels of community integration.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","38645"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522025","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-06-09","<p>The national air quality plan for nitrogen dioxide we published last December set out that we would consult on a framework for Clean Air Zones later this year.</p><p> </p><p>Clean Air Zones encompass the Low Emission Zone approach of discouraging access to more polluting vehicles but will also act as a focus for integrating wider action to improve air quality. For example, they will bring together action to accelerate the transition to ultra low emission vehicles and innovative approaches to improving air quality and will support local growth.</p><p> </p><p>The framework will be non-statutory guidance which will set out the important principles that need to be consistent in how Clean Air Zones should be implemented, such as which vehicle standards to apply. In this way it will seek to ensure that Zones are implemented in the same way by local authorities across England.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-06-09T09:36:46.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522025/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522025/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522025/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-05-26","Low Emission Zones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what requirements are in place to ensure that local authorities seeking to introduce a low emission zone follow government guidance when so doing; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","38703"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522026","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-06","<p>This government is committed to reducing litter and have put in place the first-ever national litter strategy.</p><p>The Government will now for the first time work with town halls, campaign groups and businesses- including fast food firms, manufacturers of chewing gum and the packaging industry- to ensure a coherent and joined-up approach.</p><p>Since the Government published its response to the CLG Select Committee Report in December I have met with a whole host of NGOs, manufacturers of commonly-littered items, members of both Houses of Parliament, and of course local government to discuss what we can be doing.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-06-06T14:01:17.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522026/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522026/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522026/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-26","Litter","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to reduce littering.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","38854"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522027","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-06","<p>I refer my Hon Friend to the Prime Minister's response of 25th May 2016. This information is not collated centrally by the Department.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2016-06-06T16:28:13.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522027/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522027/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522027/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-26","Department for Communities and Local Government: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 25 May 2016 to Question 37198, how many of the leaflets entitled Why the Government believes that voting to remain in the European Union is the best decision for the UK have been returned to his Department; and what the postage cost to the Government has been of such returns.","true","Biography information for Tom Pursglove","Corby","Tom Pursglove","38766"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522028","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-06","<p>Copies of the Government's published documents on the Referendum are available in the Libraries of both Houses. It is not normal practice to publish letters to members of the public and stakeholders. Costs relating to the Referendum will be accounted for in the usual way in Annual Report and Accounts.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2016-06-06T16:27:38.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522028/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522028/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522028/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-26","Department for Communities and Local Government: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will place in the Library copies of all letters, leaflets and other material from his Department circulated to (a) stakeholders and (b) members of the public on the EU Referendum; what the costs of the production and distribution of that material has been since 1 January 2016; and what he estimates the cost of any further production and distribution of such material will be between 6 May 2016 and 23 June 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","William Wragg","38812"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522029","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-06","<p>The Housing Act 1996 provides that certain people are given a priority need for accommodation. They include households with dependent children, pregnant women and those who are vulnerable. A person can be vulnerable as a result of old age, mental or physical illness or disability or for any other special reason. Other priority need categories include, but are not limited to, those who are vulnerable as a result of serving in her Majesty’s Armed Services, being a looked after child, fleeing violence or abuse, or are homeless as a result of an emergency such as a flood, fire or other disaster.</p><p>However it is better to prevent a homelessness crisis happening in the first place than to expose households to the stress and upheaval of homelessness. That is why Government has maintained and protected homelessness prevention funding for local authorities through the local government finance settlement totalling £315 million by 2019/20. We want to go further to put prevention at the heart of our approach to homelessness and in December 2015, I made a commitment to work with homelessness organisations and across Departments to consider options, including legislation, to prevent more people from becoming homeless.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-06-06T13:55:59.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522029/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522029/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522029/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-26","Homelessness: Temporary Accommodation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment his Department has made of the efficacy of the current priority need system for allocating emergency housing in preventing homelessness.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","38807"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522030","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-08","Since 2014, the number of UK premises with 4G coverage has increased by 17% - to 90% in 2015. In addition, more than 99% of UK premises have mobile coverage (Ofcom 2015 Connected Nations Report, <a href="http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/market-data-research/market-data/infrastructure/connected-nations-2015/" target="_blank">http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/market-data-research/market-data/infrastructure/connected-nations-2015/</a>). Coverage will improve further as mobile operators upgrade and extend their network to meet the licence obligations arising from the Government's December 2014 agreement requiring each operator to provide voice coverage to at least 90% of the UK's landmass by 2017.<p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-06-08T12:59:03.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522030/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522030/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522030/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-26","Mobile Phones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what the proportion of increased coverage of mobile signal to UK premises is since the December 2014 agreement with the four mobile network operators was secured.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","38736"
