"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522093","Department of Health","false","2016-06-09","<p>Monitoring food businesses to ensure compliance with legislation on food labelling and composition is the responsibility of county councils, unitary authorities, the London Boroughs and some but not all metropolitan borough councils. These local authorities are also responsible for taking enforcement action, including prosecutions, where non-compliance is found.</p><p> </p><p>Data are reported to the Food Standards Agency (FSA) on the number of food and drink analyses undertaken in relation to compositional issues and labelling and presentation issues:</p><p>23,599 analyses were undertaken in 2014/15, 16,899 for compositional issues and 6,700 for labelling and presentation issues.</p><p>29,324 analyses were undertaken in 2013/14, 19,386 for compositional issues and 9,938 for labelling and presentation issues.</p><p>26,940 analyses were undertaken in 2012/13, 16,982 for compositional issues and 9,958 for labelling and presentation issues.</p><p> </p><p>Data are also reported to the FSA on the total number of prosecutions concluded for food standards issues. This includes action in relation to composition, labelling and presentation but also for other issues such as chemical contamination. In 2014/15, 2013/14 and 2012/13 respectively, 75, 57 and 78 United Kingdom food establishments were subject to prosecution.</p><p> </p><p>The FSA has recently established a central register of successful food law prosecutions. Analysis of data collected for the first year of operation of the register is not yet complete, but in future it will provide more definitive data on prosecutions for offences of this nature.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","38647 ; 38648 ; 38649 ; 38650","2016-06-09T11:39:37.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522093/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522093/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522093/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Meat: Origin Marking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many (a) incidents have been reported to trading standards teams of and (b) prosecutions have taken place for packing and selling beef and poultry with an unknown origin in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","38651"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522094","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-06-07","<p>Proposals on the listing protection of 60 species have been submitted to the 17<sup>th</sup> Conference of Parties (CoP17) to the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES). Uplisting proposals for elephants and lions will be discussed but there is no proposal on rhinoceroses, which are already generally subject to the highest level of protection.</p><p> </p><p>All these proposals will be assessed against the scientific criteria for listings set out in the Convention and, where justified, the UK will advocate further protection to support the survival of endangered species. This includes in negotiations with the other Member States of the EU to ensure our positions on proposals are taken into account before the final negotiating position for the EU and its Member States is agreed.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-06-07T10:21:32.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522094/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522094/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522094/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-05-26","Nature Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what the Government's policy will be on supporting further protection through an uplisting of (a) elephants, (b) rhinos and (c) lions at the forthcoming CITES Conference of the Parties in September 2016.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","38789"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522095","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-06-06","<p>The Government accepts that fireworks can have a detrimental effect on some animals. However, we consider that if users follow the correct and sensible use of fireworks combined with owners of animals taking certain precautions, these can help to avoid or reduce any detrimental effects.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-06-06T14:59:32.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522095/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522095/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522095/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-05-26","Animal Welfare: Fireworks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the effect of fireworks on animal welfare.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","38937"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522096","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-06-06","<p>The objective of the review of EU legislation on veterinary medicines and medicated feeds includes tackling the threat of antibiotic resistance. The government supports measures that will provide a framework for reducing the use of antibiotics in livestock, including restrictions on preventative use.</p><p> </p><p>When one or more animals have been exposed to a bacterial disease threat and could be sub-clinically infected, the metaphylactic use of antibiotics may be essential to maintain health and welfare.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-06-06T13:15:47.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522096/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522096/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522096/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-05-26","Livestock: Antibiotics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what the Government's policy is on (a) European Commission and Parliament proposals to reduce the routine overuse of antibiotics in farming and (b) proposals for (i) an EU-wide ban on the routine use of antibiotics in groups of food-producing animals where no disease has been diagnosed in any of the animals and (ii) restrictions on metaphylactic use.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","38945"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522097","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-06","The European Court of Justice (ECJ) does not publish figures relating to the nationality of its staff. According to our own internal records, there were 67 UK nationals on the staff of the ECJ in 2013. We do not hold records for the other years.","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-06-06T15:24:56.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522097/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522097/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522097/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-26","European Court of Justice: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many UK nationals has been on the staff of the European Court of Justice in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","38671"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522098","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>The European Court of Auditors (ECA) does not publish figures relating to its staff numbers and nationality. According to our own internal records, the following number of UK nationals have been on the staff of the ECA since 2010:<br>2010: 51<br>2011: 50<br>2012: No records held<br>2013: 50<br>2014: 50<br>2015: 49<br>2016: 50</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-06-06T15:32:47.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522098/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522098/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522098/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-26","European Court of Auditors: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many UK nationals have been on the staff of the European Court of Auditors in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","38672"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522099","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-06","The European Commission publishes data on its permanent EU officials (excluding seconded national experts) broken down by nationality and by each of its Directorates-General and services at the following link: http://ec.europa.eu/civil_service/about/figures/index_en.htm","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-06-06T15:33:29.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522099/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522099/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522099/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-26","EU Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many UK nationals have been on the staff of (a) each of the Directorates-General and (b) other services of the European Commission in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","38673"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522100","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>The EU staffing unit, established in April 2013, promotes EU careers across the UK and supports candidates through the application process. It has increased secondments in positions of strategic importance to the UK. The European Fast Stream within the Civil Service has also been re-launched.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-06-06T15:43:59.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522100/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522100/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522100/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-26","EU Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to encourage more UK nationals to take up traineeships in the European Parliament and European Commission.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","38674"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522101","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>The Forfeiture Committee which makes recommendations on the removal of honours can consider any case where there is evidence to suggest that the retention of an honour would bring the honours system into disrepute, for example, if an individual has been found guilty by the Courts of a criminal offence and sentenced to a term of imprisonment; or has been censured/struck off by the relevant Regulatory Authority or Professional Body for actions or failures to act which are directly relevant to the granting of the Honour.</p><p>Honours nominations are considered by one of the nine independent honours selection committees. There are many reasons why a nomination may not be successful when judged on merit against other nominations.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-06-06T10:15:58.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522101/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522101/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522101/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-05-26","Honours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what criteria are used for decisions on the (a) removal and (b) denial of UK honours.","false","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","38694"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522102","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-08","<p>As the Prime Minister, the Member for Witney (David Cameron) has said, there is a very strong case for saying that the atrocities committed by Daesh amount to genocide, but recognition of genocide should be a matter for international courts, not political bodies.</p><p>When an attempt was made in 2014 to have the UN Security Council refer the situation in Syria to the International Criminal Court, it was vetoed by Russia and China. We have no reason to believe another referral would deliver a different outcome.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2016-06-08T13:27:59.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522102/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522102/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522102/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-26","Middle East: Genocide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will initiate a resolution of the UN Security Council related to whether genocide is being committed against religious minorities in Syria and Iraq.","false","Biography information for Dawn Butler","Brent Central","Dawn Butler","38614"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522103","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-10","The central element of the deal that the Government has secured is an International Law Decision agreed by all the Heads of State or Government of the Member States of the EU. It is legally-binding under international law and will take effect if the British people vote to remain in the EU. The Decision also includes a legally binding and irreversible commitment that the Member States will at the next opportunity, and subject to compliance with their respective constitutional requirements and the procedures in the EU Treaties, amend the EU Treaties to address key UK concerns.","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-06-10T13:47:40.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522103/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522103/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522103/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-26","European Union","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, when he expects negotiations on the new EU treaty to incorporate the new settlement for the UK in the EU to begin in the event of the UK voting to stay in the EU.","false","Biography information for John Redwood","Wokingham","John Redwood","38603"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522104","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-10","British citizens living in the EU currently enjoy a range of rights to live, to work and to access pensions, health care and public services that are guaranteed through EU law. There would be no requirement under EU law for these rights to be maintained if the UK left the EU. Should an agreement be reached to maintain these rights, the expectation must be that this would have to be reciprocated for EU citizens in the UK.","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-06-10T14:03:11.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522104/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522104/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522104/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-26","British Nationals Abroad: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what legal status UK citizens currently resident elsewhere in the EU will have in the event of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","38794"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522105","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>We consistently raise our concerns about the treatment of the Baha’i community in Iran with the Iranian Government. We call on Iran to cease harassment of all religious minorities and to fulfil its international and domestic obligations to allow freedom of religion to all Iranians.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-06-06T13:42:17.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522105/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522105/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522105/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-26","Iran: Baha'i Faith","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent reports he has received on allegations of torture and threats of physical and sexual violence against Baha'is sentenced to prison terms in Golestan province, Iran.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","38802"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522106","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>We are aware of several public reports regarding alleged events in Cizre. We agree with the UN High Commissioner for Human Rights, Zeid Ráad al Hussein that it is essential that authorities respect human rights at all times while undertaking security or counter-terrorism operations.</p><p>We believe Turkey has a legitimate right to defend itself against the PKK, a terrorist organisation which has killed hundreds of innocent people in the past year. A PKK offshoot - the Kurdistan Freedom Falcons, or TAK - has also claimed responsibility for a number of recent attacks, including an indiscriminate suicide car bombing in central Ankara on 13 March that killed over 30 people. Our thoughts are with the victims of PKK attacks, and the civilians who have been caught up in the recent conflict.</p><p>Our Ambassador to Turkey and I have discussed with the Turkish government the importance of respecting human rights and avoiding civilian casualties in the fight against terrorism. We believe the first responsibility for investigating any alleged violations falls to Turkey. And that the PKK needs to cease violence in order to create the conditions for political resolution of the difficulties in the south east.</p>","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond","38761 ; 38763","2016-06-06T16:52:26.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522106/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522106/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522106/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-26","Turkey: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to the statement of the UN High Commissioner for Human Rights, Zeid Ráad al Hussein, of 10 May 2016, what his policy is on the government of Turkey conducting prompt and independent investigations into alleged violations of human rights by Turkish security forces, alleged extra-judicial killings and disproportionate use of force.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","38762"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522107","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-10","<p>Burma’s new Government have made rule of law a priority of their administration. It is clear that this will entail significant legislative reform and the, newly formed, Legal Affairs and Special Cases Assessment Commission has identified 142 priority laws for repeal or amendment. Both The Prime Minister, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron) and the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond) have offered Aung San Suu Kyi whatever assistance her Government requires as they set about the process of democratic reform.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-06-10T12:56:19.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522107/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522107/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522107/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-26","Burma: Legislation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions the Government has had with the Burmese government on repealing or amending provisions of that country's (a) penal code, (b) Peaceful Assembly Act, (c) Unlawful Associations Act 1908, (d) Telecommunications Act 2013, (e) Official Secrets Act 1923 and (f) other laws that affect the rights to freedom of expression, peaceful assembly and association.","false","Biography information for Ann Clwyd","Cynon Valley","Ann Clwyd","38796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522108","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>We are aware of several public reports regarding alleged events in Cizre. We agree with the UN High Commissioner for Human Rights, Zeid Ráad al Hussein that it is essential that authorities respect human rights at all times while undertaking security or counter-terrorism operations.</p><p>We believe Turkey has a legitimate right to defend itself against the PKK, a terrorist organisation which has killed hundreds of innocent people in the past year. A PKK offshoot - the Kurdistan Freedom Falcons, or TAK - has also claimed responsibility for a number of recent attacks, including an indiscriminate suicide car bombing in central Ankara on 13 March that killed over 30 people. Our thoughts are with the victims of PKK attacks, and the civilians who have been caught up in the recent conflict.</p><p>Our Ambassador to Turkey and I have discussed with the Turkish government the importance of respecting human rights and avoiding civilian casualties in the fight against terrorism. We believe the first responsibility for investigating any alleged violations falls to Turkey. And that the PKK needs to cease violence in order to create the conditions for political resolution of the difficulties in the south east.</p>","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond","38761 ; 38762","2016-06-06T16:52:26.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522108/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522108/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522108/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-26","Turkey: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to the statement of the UN High Commissioner for Human Rights, Zeid Ráad al Hussein, of 10 May 2016, what his policy is on the government of Turkey giving independent investigators, including UN staff, unimpeded access to South East Turkey to investigate alleged violations of human rights.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","38763"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522109","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-09","<p>We have had no specific reporting nor have we made representations on behalf of the group mentioned. However, we consistently raise our concerns about the treatment of the Baha’i community in Iran with the Iranian Government. We call on Iran to cease harassment of all religious minorities and to fulfil its international and domestic obligations to allow freedom of religion to all Iranians.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-06-09T14:17:29.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522109/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522109/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522109/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-26","Iran: Baha'i Faith","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports he has received on (a) the mass arrest of members of the Baha'i community in Golestan province, Iran and (b) the length of their sentence of imprisonment.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","38797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522110","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>We are aware of several public reports regarding alleged events in Cizre. We agree with the UN High Commissioner for Human Rights, Zeid Ráad al Hussein that it is essential that authorities respect human rights at all times while undertaking security or counter-terrorism operations.</p><p>We believe Turkey has a legitimate right to defend itself against the PKK, a terrorist organisation which has killed hundreds of innocent people in the past year. A PKK offshoot - the Kurdistan Freedom Falcons, or TAK - has also claimed responsibility for a number of recent attacks, including an indiscriminate suicide car bombing in central Ankara on 13 March that killed over 30 people. Our thoughts are with the victims of PKK attacks, and the civilians who have been caught up in the recent conflict.</p><p>Our Ambassador to Turkey and I have discussed with the Turkish government the importance of respecting human rights and avoiding civilian casualties in the fight against terrorism. We believe the first responsibility for investigating any alleged violations falls to Turkey. And that the PKK needs to cease violence in order to create the conditions for political resolution of the difficulties in the south east.</p>","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond","38762 ; 38763","2016-06-06T16:52:26.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522110/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522110/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522110/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-26","Turkey: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports he has received on alleged serious abuses of human rights by Turkish security forces in Cizre.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","38761"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522111","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-07","<p>We strongly support the right to freedom of thought, conscience and religion, which is restricted in Saudi Arabia, reflecting views which are widely held in Saudi society. The authorities are encouraging reforms at a pace that is acceptable to Saudi society. This includes allowing foreign workers in Saudi Arabia to practice religions other than Islam in private.</p><p>We regularly raise human rights issues, including in relation to the right to freedom of thought, conscience and religion, with the Saudi Arabian authorities.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-06-07T16:01:17.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522111/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522111/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522111/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-26","Saudi Arabia: Religious Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking to promote religious freedom in Saudi Arabia; and what recent representations the Government has made to Saudi Arabia on that matter.","false","Biography information for Dawn Butler","Brent Central","Dawn Butler","38785"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522112","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-10","I refer my Hon Friend to the Prime Minister's response of 25th May 2016. This information is not collated centrally by the Department.","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-06-10T14:01:35.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522112/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522112/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522112/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-26","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 25 May 2016 to Question 37198, how many of the leaflets entitled Why the Government believes that voting to remain in the European Union is the best decision for the UK have been returned to his Department; and what the postage cost to the Government has been of such returns.","true","Biography information for Tom Pursglove","Corby","Tom Pursglove","38772"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522113","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>I am deeply concerned by this report of the horrors and misery endured by ordinary Libyan civilians living under Daesh. I condemn their barbaric and appalling crimes in Sirte and elsewhere in Libya. It is vital that those responsible are held accountable. Political instability and conflict in Libya, after 40 years of Gaddafi misrule, created the conditions for Daesh to become established. Only an inclusive government will deliver the peace and stability that the Libyan people desire and deny the space for Daesh and other extremist groups to operate.</p><p>Our consistent policy has been to support a lasting and inclusive political agreement and the establishment of a Government of National Accord (GNA) as the best way to tackle the threat in the long term. Following the Libyan Political Agreement, signed in December 2015, we now have a GNA, and the Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond) visited Tripoli on 18 April to discuss how we could help the GNA bolster security and tackle Daesh. We have allocated £10 million in this financial year to help restore stability in Libya; rebuild the economy; fight Daesh; and tackle the criminal gangs that fuel illegal migration.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-06-06T14:02:39.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522113/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522113/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522113/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-26","Libya: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will make an assessment of the implications for his policies of the finding of the report from Human Rights Watch entitled, We Feel We Are Cursed: Life under ISIS in Sirte, Libya, published on 18 May 2016.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","38725"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522114","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-10","<p>I refer my hon. Friend to the answer given by my hon. Friend the Member for Weston-super-Mare, the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State at the Cabinet Office (John Penrose) on the 9th June 2016 in response to PQ <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=38825" target="_blank">38825</a>.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-06-10T14:17:00.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522114/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522114/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522114/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-26","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will place in the Library copies of all letters, leaflets and other material from his Department circulated to (a) stakeholders and (b) members of the public on the EU referendum; what the costs of the production and distribution of that material have been since 1 January 2016; and what he estimates the cost of any further production and distribution of such material will be between 6 May 2016 and 23 June 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","William Wragg","38818"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522115","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>We have made no specific representations on behalf of the group mentioned. However, we consistently raise our concerns about the treatment of the Baha’i community in Iran with the Iranian Government. We call on Iran to cease harassment of all religious minorities and to fulfil its international and domestic obligations to allow freedom of religion to all Iranians.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-06-06T13:41:29.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522115/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522115/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522115/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-26","Iran: Baha'i Faith","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to his Iranian counterpart on allegations that Baha'i people sentenced to prison terms in Golestan province were tortured, forced to sign confessions and denied access to legal representation.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","38733"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522116","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-10","The Instrument for Pre-Accession Assistance is used in Turkey to promote cooperation on a range of issues that matter to the UK, such as migration management and organised crime. The Department does not hold figures for the funds used for strengthening Turkey’s external border.","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-06-10T13:59:28.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522116/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522116/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522116/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-26","Turkey: EU Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the EU budget is for assistance to Turkey for strengthening its external border with Syria, Iran and Iraq in (a) 2016-17 and (b) 2017-18.","false","Biography information for John Redwood","Wokingham","John Redwood","38750"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522117","Department of Health","false","2016-06-09","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given by the Minister for the Cabinet Office on 8 June 2016 to Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-05-26/38811/" target="_blank">38811</a>.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-06-09T08:07:46.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522117/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522117/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522117/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Department of Health: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will place in the Library copies of all letters, leaflets and other material from his Department circulated to (a) stakeholders and (b) members of the public on the EU referendum; what the costs of the production and distribution of that material has been since 1 January 2016; and what he estimates the cost of any further production and distribution of such material will be between 6 May 2016 and 23 June 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","William Wragg","38820"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522118","Department of Health","false","2016-06-07","<p>We have no plans to make such an assessment. The Department’s policies and advice are informed by the best available evidence.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-06-07T10:55:51.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522118/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522118/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522118/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Health Education: Publications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of bringing forward legislative proposals to prevent the publication of books, papers and  other material containing health advice which does not have a sound evidence base; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","38715"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522119","Department of Health","false","2016-06-07","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the Prime Minister's response of 25 May 2016. This information is not collated centrally by the Department.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-06-07T11:01:13.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522119/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522119/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522119/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Department of Health: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 25 May 2016 to Question 37198, how many of the leaflets entitled Why the Government believes that voting to remain in the European Union is the best decision for the UK have been returned to his Department; and what the postage cost to the Government has been of such returns.","true","Biography information for Tom Pursglove","Corby","Tom Pursglove","38773"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522120","Department of Health","false","2016-06-09","<p>Tackling healthcare associated infections is complex and requires a strong patient safety system that integrates cleanliness, infection prevention and control and antibiotic use. Hand hygiene is an important component and we continuously review and enhance national measures, systems and guidance. For example hand hygiene references in <em>The Health and Social Care Act 2008 Code of Practice for prevention and control of infections and related guidance</em>, were strengthened when it was revised in 2015. It will also form part of forthcoming guidance on reducing Gram negative infections such as E. coli.</p><p>Auditing of hand hygiene is a local responsibility and information on hand hygiene compliance is not collected centrally. Therefore, no national assessment has been made of the potential links between hand hygiene compliance levels and the above infections.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","38666 ; 38667 ; 38735","2016-06-09T10:15:59.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522120/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522120/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522120/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Clostridium","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of potential links between hand hygiene compliance levels across the NHS and rates of C. Difficile bacteraemia in 2015.","false","Biography information for Nigel Mills","Amber Valley","Nigel Mills","38734"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522121","Department of Health","false","2016-06-09","<p>Tackling healthcare associated infections is complex and requires a strong patient safety system that integrates cleanliness, infection prevention and control and antibiotic use. Hand hygiene is an important component and we continuously review and enhance national measures, systems and guidance. For example hand hygiene references in <em>The Health and Social Care Act 2008 Code of Practice for prevention and control of infections and related guidance</em>, were strengthened when it was revised in 2015. It will also form part of forthcoming guidance on reducing Gram negative infections such as E. coli.</p><p>Auditing of hand hygiene is a local responsibility and information on hand hygiene compliance is not collected centrally. Therefore, no national assessment has been made of the potential links between hand hygiene compliance levels and the above infections.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","38666 ; 38667 ; 38734","2016-06-09T10:15:59.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522121/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522121/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522121/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","MSSA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of potential links between hand hygiene compliance levels across the NHS and rates of MSSA bacteraemia in 2015.","false","Biography information for Nigel Mills","Amber Valley","Nigel Mills","38735"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522122","Department of Health","false","2016-06-07","<p>Neither the Department nor the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence has any plans to do so.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-06-07T11:20:26.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522122/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522122/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522122/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Clinical Audit: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans his Department has to review and update NICE guidance to take account of emerging new technologies in electronic auditing.","false","Biography information for Nigel Mills","Amber Valley","Nigel Mills","38786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522123","Department of Health","false","2016-06-07","<p>These data are not held centrally by the Department.</p><p>Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome (EDS) is a complex group of heritable disorders of connective tissue with an estimated prevalence of one in 20,000. As EDS appears in a variety of forms rates of diagnosis can be underestimated.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-06-07T11:21:46.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522123/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522123/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522123/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome: Diagnosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many cases of Ehlers-Danios Syndrome have been diagnosed in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Wendy Morton","Aldridge-Brownhills","Wendy Morton","38845"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522124","Department of Health","false","2016-06-10","<p>I am aware of the document from the Nordic Cochrane Centre. Whilst the issues raised are a matter for the European Medicines Agency (EMA), we are satisfied that the EMA has adequate processes in place to manage any potential conflicts of interest of its scientific experts and to uphold the integrity and impartiality of its decision-making. There was consensus agreement amongst EU Member States on the conclusions of the recent human papilloma virus (HPV) vaccine safety review, and we have confidence in the outcome of this review.</p><p> </p><p>Aside from the EMA review, the World Health Organization’s Global Advisory Committee on Vaccine Safety advised in December 2015 that it had not found any safety issues to date that would alter its recommendation to use the vaccine. It concluded that there is no evidence that postural orthostatic tachycardia syndrome and complex regional pain syndrome are associated with HPV vaccination. Thorough reviews undertaken by the US Centre for Disease Control and Prevention and Health Canada have also concluded that available evidence does not support a link between HPV vaccine and development of serious and chronic illnesses.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-06-10T11:11:57.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522124/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522124/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522124/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","European Medicines Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether the Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Public Health has seen the complaint by the Nordic Cochrane Centre to the European Medicines Agency regarding maladministration at that organisation; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","38834"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522125","Department of Health","false","2016-06-07","<p>The requirements for the pharmacovigilance functions of the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency (MHRA) are set out in European legislation through Directive 2010/84/EU and Regulation (EU) No 1235/2010 and in the Human Medicines Regulations 2012. MHRA is required to carry out independent audits of these pharmacovigilance functions and report to the European Commission every two years. This is in addition to routine reporting to the Commission on Human Medicines.</p><p>The requirements on private companies in the pharmaceutical industry that hold Marketing Authorisations for medicinal products are also set out in the same legislation and the MHRA carry out inspections to ensure these companies are compliant with the requirements. The MHRA has contact with pharmaceutical companies in its day to day business as necessary to fulfil the requirements of its pharmacovigilance functions.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-06-07T11:19:19.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522125/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522125/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522125/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what compliance procedures the Medicines and Healthcare Products Regulatory Agency has to ensure that its pharmacovigilance functions do not conflict with the relationships it builds with private companies when seeking business from such companies.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","38832"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522126","Department of Health","true","2016-06-07","<p>There are <del class="ministerial">two</del> <ins class="ministerial">three </ins>human papilloma virus vaccines licensed in the European Union: Cervarix<ins class="ministerial">,</ins> <del class="ministerial">and</del> <ins class="ministerial">Gardasil and </ins>Gardasil 9. These products are licensed centrally throughout Europe by the European Commission via the European Medicines Agency (EMA). Applicants for centrally authorised products are required to submit all relevant supporting clinical trials data, whether published or not, to the EMA directly and not to the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency.</p><p> </p><p>Under current medicines legislation, the EMA database registers all EU-approved clinical trials of investigational medicinal products. Since March 2011 this information has been publicly accessible through the EU Clinical Trials Register (except adult Phase 1 trials). The EU Clinical Trials Register includes all EU-conducted trials since May 2004 when the Clinical Trials Directive was implemented and can be found here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.clinicaltrialsregister.eu/ctr-search/search" target="_blank">https://www.clinicaltrialsregister.eu/ctr-search/search</a></p><p> </p><p>Furthermore since July 2014 clinical trial sponsors have been required to provide a summary of their trial results uploaded onto the EU Clinical Trials Register within one year of their trial completing. There is a two year programme of back-loading underway to provide summaries of trial results for all trials on the Register back to when the EudraCT database was initiated in May 2004.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-06-07T10:57:37.313Z","2016-06-13T10:14:27.603Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522126/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522126/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522126/answer","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522126/answer/previousversion/2228","Biography information for George Freeman","17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Human Papillomavirus: Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether the Medicines and Healthcare Products Regulatory Agency holds any clinical trial data for HPV vaccines which is not in the public domain.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","38833"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522127","Department of Health","false","2016-06-10","<p>The Vaccine Damage Payments Scheme (VDPS) was set up under the Vaccine Damage Payments Act 1979 to provide a measure of financial help in those very rare circumstances where it is established that severe disability was caused by vaccination administered by the National Health Service.</p><p> </p><p>It is only one part of the wide range of support and help available to severely disabled people in the United Kingdom. The VDPS does not prejudice the right of the injured person to pursue a claim for compensation against the manufacturer of the vaccine.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-06-10T11:11:08.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522127/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522127/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522127/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what measures are in place to support people who have had adverse reactions to vaccines administered by the NHS.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","38831"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522128","Department of Health","false","2016-06-09","<p>The commissioning of services for people with chronic fatigue syndrome/myalgic encephalomyelitis (CFS/ME), is a local matter. To support the local NHS in shaping services for people with CFS/ME, the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) has published a clinical guideline on the management of CFS/ME in adults and children, which set outs best practice on the care, treatment and support of people with the condition.</p><p> </p><p>Although there is no cure for CFS/ME, there are treatments that may help to ease symptoms. The NICE guideline on CFS/ME recommends treatment such as cognitive behavioral therapy and graded exercise therapy approaches, which have the clearest research evidence of benefit. However, the guideline is clear that there is no one form of treatment to suit every patient. Treatment approaches will not be appropriate for all patients and the needs and preferences of patients should be taken into account. Shared decision-making between patients and healthcare professionals should take place during diagnosis and all phases of care. Furthermore, patients should be offered information about local and national self-help groups and support groups for people with CFS/ME and their carers.</p><p> </p><p>NICE last reviewed the guidance with its stakeholders, including CFS/ME charities during 2013. The review found no update was required. The full guideline may be viewed on the NICE website at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/cg53" target="_blank">www.nice.org.uk/guidance/cg53</a></p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-06-09T10:59:19.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522128/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522128/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522128/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Chronic Fatigue Syndrome","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to address barriers faced by people with ME in accessing care and support; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","38801"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522129","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-06","<p>A wide range of data shows that children in the UK are consuming too much sugar, and this is a cause of obesity and a driver of obesity-related disease. A single 330ml can of cola may contain 9 teaspoons of added sugar, which is more than a child’s daily recommended intake. This is why the government has announced an industry levy designed to encourage producers to reduce the amount of added sugar in drinks.</p><p> </p><p>The most recent published National Diet and Nutrition Survey (NDNS) includes data from 2008 to 2012. It reports that sugar sweetened soft drinks are a major contributor to daily sugar intake for children, accounting for about 30% of the daily sugar intake alone.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-06-06T14:25:01.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522129/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522129/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522129/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-26","Soft Drinks: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what data from which year of the National Diet and Nutrition Survey has been  used to inform the development of the soft drinks industry levy.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","38608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522130","Department of Health","false","2016-06-06","<p>The information is not held in the format requested.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-06-06T14:17:05.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522130/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522130/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522130/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Dementia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many emergency readmissions within 28 days of discharge there were for patients with a primary or secondary diagnosis of dementia in (a) England and (b) each clinical commissioning group and primary care trust area in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Barbara Keeley","Worsley and Eccles South","Barbara Keeley","38623"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522131","Department of Health","false","2016-06-06","<p>The information is not held in the format requested.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","38622","2016-06-06T15:11:38.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522131/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522131/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522131/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Hospitals: Discharges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many patients were discharged from hospital between 11pm and 6am in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Barbara Keeley","Worsley and Eccles South","Barbara Keeley","38624"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522132","Department of Health","false","2016-06-06","<p>This is a matter for NHS Improvement. We are informed by NHS Improvement that no payment was made by the NHS Trust Development Authority (NHS TDA) in connection with Bernie Cuthel’s secondment and employment at Manchester Mental Health and Social Care NHS Trust or her employment at the Betsi Cadwaladr Health Board. The NHS TDA became part of NHS Improvement in April 2016.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-06-06T16:08:23.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522132/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522132/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522132/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Bernie Cuthel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much was paid by the NHS Trust Development Authority to meet the salary costs of the former Chief Executive of Liverpool Community Trust, Bernie Cuthell, during her (a) secondment to Manchester Mental Health Trust and (b) employment at the Betsi Cadwaladr NHS Trust.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","38629"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522133","Department of Health","false","2016-06-06","<p>NHS England has advised that two surgeries in West Sussex have closed their practice lists. This information does not account for any practice list closure that may have occurred in April 2016 and May 2016.</p><p> </p><p>Ship Street Surgery in East Grinstead applied to formally close their patient list to new patient registrations, which was approved for a six month period from 1 April 2016, with a review after three months. Additionally, Bridge Medical Centre in Crawley also recently applied to NHS England to formally close its list to new patients, which was approved for a period of 12 months from 1 April 2016 to 31 March 2017, subject to a review at three months.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England advises there has been increased demand on general practitioner services in the area due to new housing developments. NHS England is working with the practices and Horsham and Mid Sussex Clinical Commissioning Group to put in place action plans to address the situation in East Grinstead.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-06-06T14:23:22.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522133/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522133/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522133/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","General Practitioners: West Sussex","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, which GP practice lists in West Sussex have been closed in the last 12 months; and for what reasons each such list was closed.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","38636"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522134","Department of Health","false","2016-06-10","<p>The Government has set a regulatory framework in place that aims to prevent the take up of e-cigarettes by children and non-smokers whilst making them freely available to smokers who wish to use them to quit tobacco use. Gateway effect is difficult to prove or disprove but to date, in the United Kingdom, we have not seen any significant use of e-cigarettes outside of existing smokers and ex-smokers.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-06-10T10:58:40.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522134/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522134/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522134/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Electronic Cigarettes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what his policy is on e-cigarettes as a potential gateway to smoking.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","38658"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522135","Department of Health","false","2016-06-06","<p>The information is not held in the format requested.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","38624","2016-06-06T15:11:38.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522135/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522135/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522135/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Hospitals: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many readmissions within 28 days of discharge from hospital there were for patients over the age of (a) 65, (b) 80 and (c) 90 in (i) England and (ii) each clinical commissioning group and primary care trust area in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Barbara Keeley","Worsley and Eccles South","Barbara Keeley","38622"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522136","Department of Health","false","2016-06-09","<p>Monitoring food businesses to ensure compliance with legislation on food labelling and composition is the responsibility of county councils, unitary authorities, the London Boroughs and some but not all metropolitan borough councils. These local authorities are also responsible for taking enforcement action, including prosecutions, where non-compliance is found.</p><p> </p><p>Data are reported to the Food Standards Agency (FSA) on the number of food and drink analyses undertaken in relation to compositional issues and labelling and presentation issues:</p><p>23,599 analyses were undertaken in 2014/15, 16,899 for compositional issues and 6,700 for labelling and presentation issues.</p><p>29,324 analyses were undertaken in 2013/14, 19,386 for compositional issues and 9,938 for labelling and presentation issues.</p><p>26,940 analyses were undertaken in 2012/13, 16,982 for compositional issues and 9,958 for labelling and presentation issues.</p><p> </p><p>Data are also reported to the FSA on the total number of prosecutions concluded for food standards issues. This includes action in relation to composition, labelling and presentation but also for other issues such as chemical contamination. In 2014/15, 2013/14 and 2012/13 respectively, 75, 57 and 78 United Kingdom food establishments were subject to prosecution.</p><p> </p><p>The FSA has recently established a central register of successful food law prosecutions. Analysis of data collected for the first year of operation of the register is not yet complete, but in future it will provide more definitive data on prosecutions for offences of this nature.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","38648 ; 38649 ; 38650 ; 38651","2016-06-09T11:39:37.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522136/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522136/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522136/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Food: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many (a) incidents have been reported to trading standards teams and (b) prosecutions there have been related to food and drink products substituted with a cheaper alternative in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","38647"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522137","Department of Health","false","2016-06-06","<p>We have made no assessment. Information on the range of services individual community pharmacies choose to provide free to their customers beyond those commissioned by the National Health Service is not collected.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-06-06T14:24:37.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522137/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522137/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522137/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Pharmacy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the effect on the range of free services offered by community pharmacies of the planned changes in funding for such pharmacies.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","38720"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522138","Department of Health","false","2016-06-06","<p>Following the reforms to higher education healthcare funding, the Government, through Health Education England, will retain the responsibility for commissioning and funding the minimum numbers of clinical placements required to produce sufficient healthcare graduates. The Government is consulting on the widest possible funding solutions to ensure there is sufficient placement capacity across the system, in order to match the expanded number of training places created by the reforms.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-06-06T13:55:37.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522138/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522138/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522138/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Nurses: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what funding has been allocated by Health Education England for clinical placements for the new nurse training places his Department plans to deliver by the end of the Parliament.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","38721"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522139","Department of Health","false","2016-06-10","<p>No such estimate has been made given the range of factors which may impact on rates of smoking tobacco and use of e-cigarettes.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-06-10T11:10:32.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522139/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522139/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522139/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Electronic Cigarettes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the proportion of e-cigarette users who will return to smoking tobacco products in the year ending May 2017 as a result of the Tobacco Products Directive.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","38712"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522140","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-15","<p>The Government announced in the 2015 Spending Review that from 1 August 2017, all new nursing, midwifery and allied health professional students will receive their funding and financial support through the standard student support system, rather than through the current NHS Bursary Scheme. The changes will enable us to lift the cap on the number of students on nursing, midwifery and allied healthcare courses and provide full time students on these courses with access to around 25% additional financial support for living costs. We expect this reform to enable universities to provide up to 10,000 additional nursing, midwifery and allied health training places over this Parliament.</p><p> </p><p>The proportion of students that will fully repay their loans is estimated for the total full time student population, rather than separately for students on different courses. On this basis, we estimate that between 45% and 50% of student loan borrowers are expected to pay off their student loan in full.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-06-15T14:42:26.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522140/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522140/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522140/answer","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522140/answer/previousversion/2171","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-05-26","Health Professions: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate his Department has made of the proportion of nursing, midwifery and allied healthcare graduates who are expected to pay off their student loan in full.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","38702"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522141","Department of Health","false","2016-06-06","<p>The information about the average length of clinical placements for nursing, midwifery and allied healthcare students taken in each year of their degree is not collected by the Department.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-06-06T13:58:03.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522141/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522141/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522141/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Health Professions: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the average length is of nursing, midwifery and allied healthcare students' clinical placements taken in each year of their degree.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","38700"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522142","Department of Health","false","2016-06-09","<p>Tackling healthcare associated infections is complex and requires a strong patient safety system that integrates cleanliness, infection prevention and control and antibiotic use. Hand hygiene is an important component and we continuously review and enhance national measures, systems and guidance. For example hand hygiene references in <em>The Health and Social Care Act 2008 Code of Practice for prevention and control of infections and related guidance</em>, were strengthened when it was revised in 2015. It will also form part of forthcoming guidance on reducing Gram negative infections such as E. coli.</p><p>Auditing of hand hygiene is a local responsibility and information on hand hygiene compliance is not collected centrally. Therefore, no national assessment has been made of the potential links between hand hygiene compliance levels and the above infections.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","38667 ; 38734 ; 38735","2016-06-09T10:15:59.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522142/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522142/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522142/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","E. coli","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the relationship between hand hygiene compliance levels across the NHS and rates of E.coli bacteraemia in 2015.","false","Biography information for Nigel Mills","Amber Valley","Nigel Mills","38666"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522143","Department of Health","false","2016-06-09","<p>Tackling healthcare associated infections is complex and requires a strong patient safety system that integrates cleanliness, infection prevention and control and antibiotic use. Hand hygiene is an important component and we continuously review and enhance national measures, systems and guidance. For example hand hygiene references in <em>The Health and Social Care Act 2008 Code of Practice for prevention and control of infections and related guidance</em>, were strengthened when it was revised in 2015. It will also form part of forthcoming guidance on reducing Gram negative infections such as E. coli.</p><p>Auditing of hand hygiene is a local responsibility and information on hand hygiene compliance is not collected centrally. Therefore, no national assessment has been made of the potential links between hand hygiene compliance levels and the above infections.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","38666 ; 38734 ; 38735","2016-06-09T10:15:59.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522143/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522143/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522143/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Hospitals: Infectious Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what measures his Department is implementing to emphasise the importance of hand hygiene in the prevention of infection in hospitals.","false","Biography information for Nigel Mills","Amber Valley","Nigel Mills","38667"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522144","Department of Health","false","2016-06-06","<p>We are advised by London Ambulance Service NHS Trust (LAS) that during 2015/16, it recruited 717 frontline staff. In doing so, LAS achieved its recruitment target and filled all its available frontline posts.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-06-06T15:59:54.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522144/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522144/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522144/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","London Ambulance Service: Paramedical Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the Answer of 12 May 2016 to Question 37016, what assessment he has made of the change in the number of full-time equivalent paramedics employed by the London Ambulance Service over the last three years.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","38685"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522145","Department of Health","false","2016-06-06","<p>The National Information Board’s strategy document <em>Personalised Health and Care 2020 </em>(published November 2014) set out the aim to support greater uptake of the use of digital systems in health and care to create a National Health Service paper free at the point of care by 2020. This will remove the system’s reliance on paper and will help reduce postal service costs for the NHS.</p><p> </p><p>In the case of appointment letters for patients the new NHS e-referral system, introduced last year, already allows healthcare providers to choose not to send out appointment letters, instead allowing patients to access the information directly from the NHS e-referral system. Patients have an option to print off the details of their appointment if they prefer to have a paper copy of the information. We expect increasing numbers of providers will use this functionality to help contain costs.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-06-06T15:15:58.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522145/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522145/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522145/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","NHS: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will take steps to reduce the cost to the NHS of postage of appointment notifications to patients.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","38670"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522147","Department of Health","false","2016-06-06","<p>Our Childhood Obesity Strategy, which will be launched in the summer, will look at everything that contributes to a child becoming overweight and obese. It will set out what more can be done by all.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","38942","2016-06-06T14:03:34.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522147/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522147/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522147/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Obesity: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether it is planned that the Government's childhood obesity strategy will include measures restricting the marketing of unhealthy foods to children.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","38943"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522148","Department of Health","false","2016-06-10","<p>The first sexual health clinics involved in the pilot started offering the human papillomavirus vaccine to men who have sex with men, who are already attending the clinic for an existing appointment, on 6 June 2016.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-06-10T11:11:30.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522148/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522148/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522148/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Human Papillomavirus: Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, on what date in June 2016 the HPV vaccination pilot for men who have sex with men is planned to commence; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","William Wragg","38848"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522149","Department of Health","false","2016-06-07","<p>Information on the peptide receptor radionuclide therapy treatments funded through the Cancer Drugs Fund (CDF) is shown in the table. It is not known for what type of cancer these treatments have been provided.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Number of patients treated in 2011/12<sup>1</sup></p></td><td><p>Number of patients treated in 2012/13<sup>1</sup></p></td><td><p>Number of CDF notifications 2013/14<sup>2</sup></p></td><td><p>Number of CDF notifications 2014/15<sup>2</sup></p></td><td><p>Number of CDF notifications 2015/16 (to Sept)<sup> 2</sup></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Peptide receptor radionuclide therapy (to include Lutetium-177 or Yttrium-90 octreotide analogues)</p></td><td><p>49</p></td><td><p>117</p></td><td><p>152</p></td><td><p>229</p></td><td><p>116</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><sup>1 </sup>Source: Strategic Health Authority returns to the Department of Health</p><p><sup>2 </sup>Source: NHS England</p><p> </p><p>Information on the number of peptide receptor radionuclide therapy treatments provided outside of the CDF is not collected.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-06-07T11:23:47.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522149/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522149/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522149/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Neuroendocrine Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what information his Department holds on the use of peptide receptor radionuclide therapy treatments to target carcinoid tumours.","false","Biography information for Mr Nicholas Brown","Newcastle upon Tyne East","Mr Nicholas Brown","38897"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522150","Department of Health","false","2016-06-07","<p>Peptide receptor radionuclide therapy (including Luththera) for the treatment of gastro-entero-pancreatic neuroendocrine tumours was removed from the Cancer Drugs Fund in November 2015 on the grounds that it represented insufficient value for retention within the Fund.</p><p>NHS England’s full decision summary is available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/ourwork/cancer/cdf/cdf-drug-sum/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/ourwork/cancer/cdf/cdf-drug-sum/</a></p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-06-07T11:25:38.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522150/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522150/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522150/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, for what reasons the Lutathera drug was removed from the list of drugs available under the Cancer Drugs Fund.","false","Biography information for Mr Nicholas Brown","Newcastle upon Tyne East","Mr Nicholas Brown","38894"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522151","Department of Health","false","2016-06-07","<p>The clinical research findings on Lutathera, presented to the European Cancer Congress, have not yet been published in a peer-reviewed journal.</p><p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) has been asked to develop technology appraisal guidance on lutetium-177 dotatate for the treatment of unresectable, somatostatin receptor-positive, gastroenteropancreatic neuroendocrine tumours. NICE’s guidance is based on a thorough assessment of the available evidence and is developed through wide consultation with stakeholders.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-06-07T11:24:39.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522151/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522151/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522151/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Neuroendocrine Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to findings presented at the 2015 European Cancer Congress on Lutathera, what assessment he has made of the reported benefits of that drug on treating patients with neuroendocrine tumours.","false","Biography information for Mr Nicholas Brown","Newcastle upon Tyne East","Mr Nicholas Brown","38895"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522152","Department of Health","false","2016-06-09","<p>The Independent Living Fund (ILF) closed on 30 June 2015, with funding and responsibility transferring to local authorities in England and the Devolved Administrations in Scotland and Wales. The Department has not made an assessment of the financial impact on those caring for family members, and at this stage does not plan to do so.</p><p> </p><p>However, the Department has issued statutory guidance to local authorities to support this transfer of responsibility and to prevent any former ILF user having their care interrupted during the transfer. I have recently reminded local authorities of the need to comply with this guidance. In addition, the Care Act 2014 introduced important new rights for carers, and placed a duty on local authorities to assess adults who appear to have care and support needs and to meet those needs which meet the national eligibility criteria.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has committed to publishing a new cross-Government National Carers Strategy before the end of 2016. A wide-ranging call for evidence is now underway to underpin the development of the Strategy, which will gather evidence from stakeholders, and carers themselves, on their experience of caring including issues of personal finance and the support they receive from local authorities.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-06-09T10:10:38.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522152/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522152/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522152/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Carers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the financial effect on people caring for family members of the closure of the Independent Living Fund and the introduction of the Care Act 2014.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","38788"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522153","Department of Health","false","2016-06-10","<p>Experience from the two Brent and Harrow clinics providing human papillomavirus vaccinations to men who have sex with men was shared with Public Health England and has helped to inform the development of the pilot. North West London is unlikely to be representative of England as a whole and the pilot will therefore let us consider provision of this vaccination programme in different geographical areas. It will also consider a wider age range than the service provided in these two clinics. The pilot will cover men up to 45 years of age in line with advice from the Joint Committee on Vaccination and Immunisation (JCVI). The pilot will help resolve a range of implementation issues and determine whether a national programme can be delivered through Genito-Urinary Medicine and HIV clinics at a cost effective price in line with the JCVI’s advice.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-06-10T10:59:07.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522153/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522153/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522153/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Human Papillomavirus: Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he made of the utility of data from the clinic in Brent and Harrow which has been providing men who have sex with men with HPV vaccinations since 2012 when determining that it was necessary to conduct an HPV vaccination pilot before deciding on a national roll-out; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","William Wragg","38847"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522154","Department of Health","false","2016-06-06","<p>Between 2010-11 and 2014-15, there was a 5.4% increase in the number of emergency admissions of patients aged 65 and over at Brighton and Sussex University Hospitals NHS Trust.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-06-06T15:49:31.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522154/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522154/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522154/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Hospitals: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what change there was in the level of emergency admissions of older people between 2010-11 and 2014-15 in the Brighton and Sussex University Hospitals NHS Trust.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","38902"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522155","Department of Health","false","2016-06-09","<p>NHS England has made an assessment of the need for national treatment decisions as to the commissioning of systemic therapies for neuroendocrine carcinomas. Based on this assessment, it has discussed the issue with the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) and NICE has agreed to do a multiple technology appraisal of lanreotide, sunitinib, everolimus and peptide receptor radionuclide therapy. NICE guidance on these treatments is due in the summer of 2017. In the meantime, sunitinib is available from the Cancer Drugs Fund and lanreotide is available through routine commissioning.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-06-09T11:34:48.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522155/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522155/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522155/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Neuroendocrine Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the adequacy of treatment and provision of support through the NHS for patients of neuroendocrine cancer.","false","Biography information for Mr Nicholas Brown","Newcastle upon Tyne East","Mr Nicholas Brown","38882"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522156","Department of Health","false","2016-06-10","<p>NHS England has advised that the Cancer Drugs Fund budget was increased to £340 million for 2015-16 and, with the new financial control and commercial mechanisms being put in place from 1 July 2016 under the new arrangements for the Fund, that budget increase will be maintained at £340 million for 2016-17.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-06-10T10:58:08.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522156/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522156/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522156/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, for what reasons the budget for the revised Cancer Drugs Fund was established at £340 million.","false","Biography information for Mr Nicholas Brown","Newcastle upon Tyne East","Mr Nicholas Brown","38896"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522157","Department of Health","false","2016-06-10","<p>As a Departmental Expert Committee the Advisory Committee on the Safety of Blood Tissues and Organs (SaBTO) does not undertake or commission research directly. SaBTO is carrying out a review of selection criteria for donation of blood, tissues and cells. The review will be wide-ranging and comprehensive and will include evidence relating to the risks of blood-borne infections in people who have previously injected drugs or received money or drugs for sex. Should any gaps be identified in the course of the review, SaBTO could make research recommendations.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-06-10T11:08:02.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522157/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522157/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522157/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Blood: Viral Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what research the Advisory Committee on the Safety of Blood, Tissues and Organs plans to undertake or commission on the risk of blood-borne viruses for former sex workers and ex-intravenous drug users.","false","Biography information for Victoria Borwick","Kensington","Victoria Borwick","38916"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522158","Department of Health","false","2016-06-06","<p>Our Childhood Obesity Strategy, which will be launched in the summer, will look at everything that contributes to a child becoming overweight and obese. It will set out what more can be done by all.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","38943","2016-06-06T14:03:34.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522158/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522158/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522158/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Obesity: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether it is planned that the Government's childhood obesity strategy will include targets for industry to reduce levels of (a) fat and (b) salt in food and drink.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","38942"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522159","Department of Health","false","2016-06-06","<p>The Department has made no such assessment. The families of children with cystic fibrosis may be eligible for social care support, continuing care in the home, and Disability Living Allowance or Personal Independence Payments, based on the level of the child or young person’s needs.</p><p>The number of children under the age of 18 with cystic fibrosis is not collected centrally. It is estimated that one in every 2,500 babies born in England has cystic fibrosis.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","38906","2016-06-06T14:20:47.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522159/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522159/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522159/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Cystic Fibrosis: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many children under the age of 18 in England have cystic fibrosis.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","38905"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522160","Department of Health","false","2016-06-06","<p>The Department has made no such assessment. The families of children with cystic fibrosis may be eligible for social care support, continuing care in the home, and Disability Living Allowance or Personal Independence Payments, based on the level of the child or young person’s needs.</p><p>The number of children under the age of 18 with cystic fibrosis is not collected centrally. It is estimated that one in every 2,500 babies born in England has cystic fibrosis.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","38905","2016-06-06T14:20:47.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522160/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522160/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522160/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Cystic Fibrosis: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will estimate the additional costs incurred by a family raising a child with cystic fibrosis.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","38906"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522161","Department of Health","false","2016-06-09","<p>The provision of neurological services is a matter for NHS England.</p><p> </p><p>Since 1 April 2013, NHS England has been responsible for commissioning specialised neurological services, which includes services for patients with neuromuscular disorders. NHS England has published a service specification for neurological care, which sets out what providers must have in place to offer evidence-based, safe and effective services. The specification can be found at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/d04-neurosci-spec-neuro.pdf" target="_blank">www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/d04-neurosci-spec-neuro.pdf</a></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>NHS England has advised that it commissions two services that provide support to people with neurological conditions:</p><p> </p><p>Firstly a diagnostic service for rare muscular disorders at specified centres:</p><p>- The limb-girdle muscular dystrophies (Newcastle)</p><p>- The congenital muscular dystrophies and myopathies (London – Dubowitz Neuromuscular Centre)</p><p>- The congenital myasthenic syndromes (Oxford)</p><p>- The muscle channelopathies (London – Institute of Neurology)</p><p> </p><p>These providers are required to provide a diagnostic service and support to the referring provider who has on-going responsibility for implementing care.</p><p> </p><p>The second are the services commissioned through Neurosciences: specialist neurology specification. Under this specification providers are required to provide neuromuscular nurses and a neuromuscular care co-ordinator. NHS England commissions the following providers to offer neurology services: Imperial College Healthcare NHS Trust, King’s College Hospital NHS Foundation Trust, Royal Free London NHS Foundation Trust, St George's University Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust, University College London Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust, Barts Health NHS Trust and Barking, Havering and Redbridge University Hospitals NHS Trust.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-06-09T11:36:20.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522161/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522161/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522161/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Neuromuscular Disorders: South East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to increase provision of neuromuscular care advisor support in (a) London and (b) the South East.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","38885"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522162","Department of Health","false","2016-06-06","<p>The Department has made no formal estimate of the costs of delayed discharges to the National Health Service or individual hospitals.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-06-06T08:39:50.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522162/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522162/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522162/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Hospitals: Discharges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the cost to (a) Brighton and Sussex University Hospitals NHS Trust and (b) West Sussex County Council of delays in discharging older patients from hospital in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","38903"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522163","Department of Health","false","2016-06-06","<p>In 2015 there were 11,907 delayed transfers of care at Brighton and Sussex University Hospitals NHS Trust.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Month</p></td><td><p>Number of delayed transfers of care (days)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>January 2015</p></td><td><p>1,194</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>February 2015</p></td><td><p>1,047</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>March 2015</p></td><td><p>958</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April 2015</p></td><td><p>824</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>May 2015</p></td><td><p>916</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jun 2015</p></td><td><p>1,098</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>July 2015</p></td><td><p>1,139</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>August 2015</p></td><td><p>1,089</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>September 2015</p></td><td><p>861</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>October 2015</p></td><td><p>1,017</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>November 2015</p></td><td><p>975</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>December 2015</p></td><td><p>789</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>11,907</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em> </em></p><p><em>Source</em>: Delayed transfers of care, NHS England</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-06-06T15:30:56.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522163/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522163/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522163/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-26","Hospital Beds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many bed days were lost due to delayed transfers of care in Brighton and Sussex University Hospitals NHS Trust in 2015.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","38904"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522164","Home Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>The Home Office maintains an active partnership with local governments across the UK, including those in Scotland, and funds Strategic Migration Partnerships to plan for the most appropriate dispersal of asylum seekers. The partnerships consider the impact on communities and local services so that adjustments to dispersal patterns can be made where appropriate.</p><p>Free access to NHS healthcare is provided to asylum seekers. Asylum Health Teams are commissioned by NHS England and Scotland to provide healthcare and screening. Strategic Migration Partnerships work with Care Commissioning Groups to plan for the health care needs of asylum seekers in their regions.</p><p>All children are entitled to free primary and secondary education. To enable access to education, internal checks are in place to triage applications involving children of school age for priority dispersal into permanent accommodation. Strategic Migration Partnerships discuss education provision as part of their local authority engagement. Asylum seekers are able to access legal advice via the Legal Aid system and are provided details of local solicitors as part of their induction into their dispersal region.</p><p>Local authorities are consulted before asylum seekers are placed in their area, so that the potential impact on communities and local services is fully considered. During discussions on widening dispersal in Scotland we are and will continue to ensure that Local Authority leads and partners on health and education, as well as the Scottish Government and the Scottish Law Society, are involved to address any concerns and to ensure the close and successful partnership working in Glasgow is replicated elsewhere.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","38917 ; 38919 ; 38940","2016-06-06T13:23:39.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522164/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522164/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522164/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-26","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what measures are in place to ensure that the appropriate health services, mental health services and sexual health services are available to asylum seekers dispersed to (a) current dispersal areas, (b) new dispersal areas and (c) Scotland.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","38920"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522165","Home Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>The Home Office provides accommodation for eligible asylum seekers via its contractual arrangements with three suppliers. Payments are made on a per person per night basis. The details of these daily rates are commercially sensitive and therefore we are unable to release this information.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-06-06T12:36:37.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522165/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522165/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522165/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-26","Compass Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what annual per-person rate her Department provides to each of its Compass contractors for the accommodation of asylum seekers.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","38941"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522166","Home Office","false","2016-06-09","<p>The Home Office is currently exploring the widening of dispersal agreements across all Scottish Local Authorities on a voluntary basis.</p><p>Once new dispersal agreements have been agreed and the location and likely demand for legal services is known, we will seek to meet with the Scottish Legal Aid Board and the Scottish Law Society on the proposals. Similar discussions will also be held with Migrant Help and other Non-Government Organisations to discuss provision of service and support.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-06-09T11:56:00.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522166/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522166/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522166/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-26","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what discussions took place between December 2015 and May 2016 between Ministers and (b) officials of her Department with the Scottish Legal Aid Board and the Law Society of Scotland on plans to widen asylum dispersal in Scotland; and whether any further such discussions are planned.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","38918"
