"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522173","Home Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>Recently published Home Office data confirms that, as at the end of March 2016 there were 107 local authorities accommodating dispersed asylum seekers. This data can be accessed via the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-january-to-march-2016/list-of-tables#asylum" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-january-to-march-2016/list-of-tables#asylum</a></p><p>Not all dispersal areas are currently housing asylum seekers; future published data will detail new dispersal areas as asylum seekers are dispersed to them.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-06-06T12:39:21.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522173/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522173/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522173/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-26","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the oral contribution of the Minister for Immigration of 3 May 2016, Official Report, column 45WH, on asylum seeker dispersal, if she will provide the names of the (a) 103 local authorities that are currently asylum dispersal areas, (b) 20 local authorities signed up to be asylum dispersal areas and (c) 28 local authorities that her Department is in discussions with to become asylum dispersal areas.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","38939"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522174","Home Office","false","2016-06-09","<p>The number of visas processed using priority visa services in 2015 is shown in the attached table. This figure includes both priority and super priority applications.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Total Priority applications resolved between 01-Jan-2015 and 31-Dec-2015</strong></td><td>561,475</td></tr><tr><td><strong>of which Super Priority applications resolved between 01-Jan-2015 and 31-Dec-2015</strong></td><td>9,400</td></tr><tr><td><strong>of which Priority applications resolved between 01-Jan-2015 and 31-Dec-2015</strong></td><td>552,075</td></tr></tbody></table><p>This is provisional management information that is subject to change. It has not been assured to the standard of Official Statistics.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-06-09T11:50:57.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522174/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522174/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522174/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-26","Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many visas were processed using the priority visa service in 2015.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","38652"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522175","Home Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>Assessments of the likely economic impact of proposed fee changes are undertaken by Home Office economists and are published online.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-06-06T12:50:03.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522175/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522175/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522175/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-26","Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effect of the planned increase in UK visa fees on the number of people coming to the UK.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","38653"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522176","Home Office","false","2016-06-08","<p>There were five priority settlement applications processed in Islamabad, Pakistan between 1 January 2015 and 31 December 2015. All of these cases were resolved within 15 days.</p><p>This data is taken from provisional management information that is subject to change. It has not been assured to the standard of Official Statistics.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-06-08T12:02:09.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522176/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522176/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522176/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-26","Pakistan: Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what proportion of settlement visas using the priority visa service were processed in Islamabad, Pakistan within (a) 10, (b) 15, (c) 30, (d) 60, (e) 90 and (f) 120 days.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","38654"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522177","Home Office","false","2016-06-09","<p>The average processing time for settlement applications made using priority visa services between 01-Jan-2015 and 31-Dec 2015 is 7.41 days.</p><p>This is a provisional management information that is subject to change. It has not been assured to the standard of Official Statistics.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-06-09T17:02:30.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522177/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522177/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522177/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-26","Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the average processing time is for settlement visas using the priority visa service.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","38655"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522178","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-10","<p>The Community Engagement Forum has met on three separate occasions and has engaged a wide range of people representing, among others, different Muslim communities. Further details on attendance were provided on 2 November 2015 in response to written Question 13090 and on 12 January 2016 to written Question 20784. The discussions at the Community Engagement Forum have informed policy development across several individual Departments, the effectiveness of which will be monitored in the usual way.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-06-10T13:25:03.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522178/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522178/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522178/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-26","Community Engagement Forum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how his Department is monitoring the effectiveness of the Community Engagement Forum; how frequently that forum has met; and how many Muslims that forum has engaged.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","38633"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522179","Home Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>Research shows that there is no single pathway into terrorism or extremism, nor is any one influence likely to be solely responsible for an individual?s radicalisation. It is a unique process for each individual, and the drivers are varied. However, analysis of case studies indicate that certain background factors, when combined with radicalising influences and an ideological opening, and in the absence of protective factors (such as supportive family or friends) can result in an individual being vulnerable to radicalisation.</p><p>The Prevent strategy safeguards vulnerable individuals by building resilience to extremist ideologies, countering the ideology that terrorists espouse, and removing access to terrorist propaganda online. We work in partnership with families and communities to support and safeguard vulnerable individuals. We are working with internet industry partners to remove more terrorist material, and are supporting civil society groups to deliver counter-narrative campaigns.</p><p>Our Channel programme provides support for those most at risk of radicalisation. It is voluntary and confidential, and support is only provided following careful assessment by experts.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","38646","2016-06-06T17:13:16.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522179/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522179/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522179/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-26","Radicalism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will estimate the number and proportion of British violent extremists who were radicalised by people promoting (a) non-violent extremism and (b) views that conflict with British values.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","38644"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522180","Home Office","false","2016-06-09","<p>It has been the practice of this Government not to make such forecasts. There are numerous different factors that can affect migration flows.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","38691 ; 38795","2016-06-09T16:37:54.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522180/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522180/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522180/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-26","Immigration Controls: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the number of prospective migrants who will be deterred from entering the UK from other EU member states upon implementation of the emergency brake.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","William Wragg","38707"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522181","Home Office","false","2016-06-14","<p>It has been the practice of this Government not to make such forecasts. There are numerous different factors that can affect migration flows. Projections of UK’s population are published by the independent Office for National Statistics. http://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/populationandmigration/populationprojections</p><p>As projections, these do not take account of the potential impact of Government policies or economic conditions. ONS produce estimates of short term migration for England and Wales https://www.ons.gov.uk/releases/shorttermmigrationestimatesforenglandandwalesmid2014estimates</p><p>The majority of those coming as ‘short term migrants’ were for the reason “other” (which includes activities such as: holidays and travelling; visiting family and friends; and working holidays).</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-06-14T16:34:27.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522181/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522181/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522181/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-26","Migration: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the potential number of short-term EU migrants who are expected to enter the UK to live and work in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","William Wragg","38706"
